Fourteen-year-old Ahmed Mohamed, an aspiring inventor, was taken into custody at MacArthur High School in Irving, Texas, after school staff and administrators mistakenly identified his self-made clock as a dangerous device. He had simply intended to present his invention to his engineering instructor. However, the visible circuit board and wires housed within a pencil box resulted in his immediate apprehension, questioning without his parents present, fingerprinting, and eventual transfer to a juvenile detention facility. This event quickly escalated, attracting widespread media attention both nationally and internationally, and prompting significant discussions about Islamophobia and racial profiling.

The incident triggered an instant and immense public outcry. Influential figures, such as then-President Barack Obama and Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg, publicly expressed their support, leading to invitations for Ahmed to visit the White House and Facebook headquarters. The hashtag #IStandWithAhmed gained global traction, underscoring worries regarding excessive responses and prejudice in educational disciplinary actions. Notably, two of these prestigious awards recognize local production professionals. Ronan Hill, an Emmy recipient in 2012, secured another nomination for outstanding sound mixing in a drama, and Carla Stronge was nominated for outstanding casting for the popular HBO production. These accolades strongly highlight the profound expertise within Northern Ireland's flourishing screen sector and bolster the region's increasing reputation as a significant global center for film and television.

NIS, an agency committed to advancing the film, television, and animation industries, has made substantial financial contributions that have been pivotal in drawing major international projects, such as this HBO series, to the area. This targeted funding offers crucial monetary aid and concurrently aids in building a resilient infrastructure and a highly skilled local workforce, thereby cementing Northern Ireland's standing as a prime filming location for significant productions.

The remarkable total of 24 Emmy nominations received by the series stands as unequivocal evidence of the successful partnership between global studios and Northern Irish professionals. It underscores the wide array of talents available throughout Northern Ireland, spanning specializations from sound engineering and casting to set design and visual effects. The individual recognition of Ronan Hill, a seasoned Emmy laureate, and Carla Stronge, a leading expert in casting, particularly brings to light the exceptional, world-class capabilities thriving within Northern Ireland's production sector. Their achievements showcase the consistently high caliber maintained across all stages of cinematic creation.

Richard Williams, Northern Ireland Screen's Chief Executive, conveyed immense satisfaction regarding these nominations. He voiced his pleasure at observing the outstanding contributions of local crew members gain recognition on such a distinguished international platform. Williams further remarked that Ronan and Carla's well-deserved nominations illuminate the extraordinary talent pool in Northern Ireland. He went on to assert that the ongoing triumph of the HBO series, parts of which were expertly shot amidst the region's stunning scenery, demonstrates Northern Ireland's substantial influence on worldwide entertainment. He concluded by stating that NIS's unwavering dedication to cultivating and backing the local screen industry consistently yields beneficial results, such as drawing in foreign investment, generating employment, and elevating the region's global standing.

Shooting portions of the series in Northern Ireland has delivered substantial economic advantages, resulting in considerable expenditure within the local economy across services, lodging, and diverse businesses. Moreover, it has created widespread employment prospects for hundreds of production and support staff. This continuous narrative of achievement validates Northern Ireland Screen's enduring objective: to cultivate a strong and dynamic creative sector capable of producing world-class material and competing internationally. The forthcoming Emmy Awards ceremony is eagerly awaited by all participants, especially the committed Northern Irish crew whose input has significantly elevated the series' artistic merit and broad appeal. The influence of such prominent productions extends beyond purely financial metrics, nurturing local pride and motivating future generations of cinematographers and creative experts. This persistent trajectory of development and global acknowledgment solidly establishes Northern Ireland as a crucial participant in the international entertainment arena, propelled by its distinctive locales, proficient personnel, and active backing from bodies like Northern Ireland Screen. The Dolphin Women's Institute (WI) in Braintree has completed an intricate series of knitted models, faithfully reproducing several of the town's most iconic landmarks, such as its church and museum. Each model, standing approximately 45 cm (18 inches) tall, features a meticulously crafted knitted exterior covering a polystyrene or cardboard core. This distinctive project was conceived to capture Braintree's essence through these miniature architectural representations. The initiative first arose during the lockdown periods, providing members with a shared objective and a creative outlet.

Under the direction of Elaine Pye, a seasoned member and accomplished knitter, the team carefully identified key structures that symbolize Braintree's rich historical narrative. Beyond the aforementioned church and museum, the collection also includes the venerable town hall, the bustling market square, and a charming old railway station, all rendered with remarkable precision.

Producing these highly detailed pieces demanded considerable dedication and countless hours. Members painstakingly created unique textures and a precise palette of colours for every facade, window, and roof section. Following the knitting phase, these individual components were meticulously trimmed and firmly affixed to their respective bases, ensuring an accurate fit and a truly lifelike appearance. The exceptional accuracy of detail in these small-scale architectural recreations is truly commendable.

Renowned for her expertise in intricate textile crafts, Elaine Pye played a pivotal role in guiding the team through the project's complexities, imparting various techniques and fostering a collaborative and supportive atmosphere. Their collective commitment has culminated in a singular exhibition, beautifully showcasing Braintree's heritage and the Dolphin WI's impressive artistic talents.

The entire collection is slated for public exhibition at various community events and venues throughout Braintree over the coming months, beginning with its premiere at the Braintree Museum. This affords both local residents and visitors a wonderful opportunity to admire the elaborate craftsmanship and view their cherished town in a fresh, endearing light. The undertaking has successfully strengthened bonds among WI members and generated significant local enthusiasm, earning praise for its originality and charm.

The Dolphin Women's Institute hopes this unique display will serve as an inspiration to others, standing as a delightful testament to their ingenuity and dedication to enhancing local community life. Although primarily focused on Braintree, the project's success has also attracted interest from adjacent WI groups, with some members in Hertfordshire expressing a desire to embark on similar creative ventures.

He said: "When you first got into the seat and opened the throttle it felt as if someone had given you a good kick up the bottom and away you went.
"It would do everything you asked of it. Compared to other aircraft it was light on the controls, you could do all the aerobatics and you would come up to speed very quickly.
"If you treated a Spitfire properly, it treated you properly. Treat it roughly or be careless with it and you were in trouble, in that it would do all sorts of things such as ground looping. It also had a very fragile undercarriage and could collapse."
Mr Costain was a member of the RAF for 37 years.
He flew operational Spitfires over Europe, north Africa, the Middle East and Burma.
He was also a Spitfire instructor during that time and became a test pilot on Spitfires at 9MU Cosford, Shropshire.
He said: "Everyone that joined the air force wanted to fly a Spitfire.
"I would say that I have flown nearly all of the operational Spitfires.
"There aren't many of us left [alive] that have flown the number of different marks of Spitfire that I have."
During and since his flying days, Mr Costain says he has often been asked if he was frightened during the war years.
He said: "I was terrified, but I was terrified of letting my own friends see that I was frightened. One made one's self very determined that you wouldn't show that.
"If you were attacked when you were flying a Spitfire during the war years, you turned hard into the attacking aircraft and they just couldn't get behind you! It was much more manoeuvrable than the German aircraft.
"I don't think we should ever forget what the Spitfire did for England. It was virtually England's saving grace."

Hank Costain, now 88 years old and residing in Charminster, a village near Dorchester, experienced his first flight in a Spitfire in 1942, when he was 19. This notable event took place several years after the Supermarine Spitfire's maiden flight on March 5, 1936, which originated from Eastleigh Aerodrome, now recognized as Southampton Airport. Mr. Costain frequently expresses immense fondness for piloting a Spitfire, famously calling the experience "absolutely marvellous." He vividly recounted the moment of takeoff: "As I secured myself in the cockpit and advanced the throttle, I felt an abrupt, mighty surge, almost like a sharp propulsion from behind. The Merlin engine's thunderous roar was colossal, a magnificent, untamed symphony of strength that reverberated not only through the aircraft's structure but deep within my very bones. It transcended mere mechanics; it transformed into an extension of myself, a remarkably responsive, almost living entity that flawlessly executed every nuanced instruction."

The Spitfire demonstrated extraordinary agility, with its controls feeling surprisingly light despite the aircraft's immense power. Once airborne, the landscape below dramatically shifted. Dorset's familiar fields and landmarks diminished into a finely detailed, miniature tableau, while the heavens above expanded into boundless infinity. In those moments, he experienced a profound sense of liberation, a complete unity with both the machine and the surrounding environment. They would execute demanding aerial stunts, pushing the plane to its operational boundaries. During rapid turns or steep climbs, the formidable G-forces pinned them firmly to their seats, generating an exceptional sense of thrill, a distinctive surge he considers unmatched by any other experience.

Mr. Costain reflected on his early training with a combination of nostalgia and a keen recognition of the grim aspects of wartime preparation. He explained that “Piloting the Supermarine Spitfire involved more than just control mastery; comprehending its individual character was equally crucial. Every aircraft possessed its own peculiarities, its specific temperament. One had to show it deference, and it would reciprocate by offering protection.” He remembered the unrelenting demands, the countless hours logged in the cockpit, and the rigorous practice routines designed to forge fledgling pilots into potent fighters. The aircraft's astonishing speed and agility, especially when contrasted with the less powerful training aircraft, was truly impressive. It marked a pivotal advancement, a marvel of engineering that positioned Britain as a leader in air combat.

For Mr. Costain, the Spitfire transcended being a mere airplane; it personified an entire epoch, a vehicle instrumental in reshaping historical events. “It guaranteed our very existence, didn't it?” he pondered, his gaze lost in the past. “It was universally acknowledged as the world's premier fighter plane. Every departure brought with it a weighty sense of duty, twinned with an overwhelming surge of pride.” He often visits airshows, his vision following the distinctive silhouette of a Spitfire as it executes elegant loops and descents, a moving reminder of his early life soaring across contemporary skies. The distinctive thrum of its engine continues to stir deep feelings, a powerful evocation of a time marked by bravery and innovation. Even after numerous decades, the memories of those flights persist with striking clarity, highlighting the deep influence the Supermarine Spitfire exerted on his personal journey and on innumerable others.

While Sébastien Ogier remained a close contender, Meeke was clearly focused on capitalizing on his impressive Rally Mexico triumph with another dominant showing in Corsica. This event is well-known for its challenging asphalt surfaces and perilous turns. His powerful opening pace unmistakably broadcasted his intention to carry forward the momentum from Mexico, where a late surge had dramatically clinched him the win.

Known as the 'Rally of 10,000 Corners', the Tour de Course presented a stark contrast to Mexico's gravel roads and high altitudes. Instead, it demanded supreme precision and unyielding confidence on its fast tarmac. Meeke, behind the wheel of his Citroen C3 WRC, appeared perfectly adapted to these demanding conditions, pushing hard right from the first kilometer. His remarkable ability to push harder on Corsica's grueling routes left his rivals, particularly championship leader Ogier, with very little room for error.

Ogier, ever the shrewd strategist, opted for a cautious approach, conserving his tyres and carefully observing Meeke's impressive rhythm. He was keenly aware that any mistake on these tight, tree-lined roads could have disastrous repercussions. This escalating contest between the two motorsport giants promised to be a classic. Meeke was not only pursuing victory but also seeking to validate his form after an inconsistent start to the season. His win in Mexico had silenced some detractors, but a strong performance here in the Tour de Course would solidify his standing as a serious title contender. All eyes now turn to the upcoming stages, where both mental and physical pressures are certain to intensify, severely testing the resolve of the Northern Irish driver and his persistent French rival.

Police have initiated a thorough investigation into this alarming incident and are appealing for public assistance. Detective Inspector Peter McFarlane, who is leading the inquiry, described the assault as "senseless and brutal." This terrifying ordeal has left both victims deeply traumatized, and law enforcement is determined to identify and apprehend those responsible. While their facial wounds were not critical, they necessitated medical attention and caused considerable distress.

DI McFarlane urged anyone who was in the vicinity of Ardencraig Quadrant or Ardencraig Drive in Castlemilk, Glasgow, at the time of the attack to contact the police. He particularly sought information from individuals who may have noticed suspicious persons in the area or possess dashcam or private CCTV recordings that could aid the investigation. Emphasizing the potential importance of even seemingly minor details in reconstructing the events and pinpointing the assailants, he also addressed the concerns of local residents. He provided reassurance that comprehensive inquiries are being conducted and that officers will maintain a visible presence on patrol to alleviate community fears.
